The original New Testament was supposed to run for a traditional 12 episodes rather than the 9 episodes that we know today. The story had progressed as far as Jesus "[[Zombie apocalypse|rising from the dead]]" and then "[[rapture|ascending to heaven]]" when a [[Christian]] writer's strike, ignited by the wise decision of Emperor [[dubya|Trajan Decius]] to feed all [[Encyclopedia Dramatica|screenwriters]] to the [[Happycat|lions]] in the arena, forced the hasty grafting on of a hurried and unconvincing season [[orgasm|climax]]. In the original plot, the risen Jesus is exposed as an emissary of the [[Ann Coulter|Devil]] sent to overturn the teachings of the original [[hippy|pacifistic guru]], and to engineer the subjugation of the [[americunts|Roman Empire]] by the new Christian [[Islam|fundamentalists]], thus leading to centuries of warfare. The plot is exposed by Judas, whose "suicide" in the [[Harry_Potter|Potter]]'s Field is really a ruse to throw off the agents of the [[Jimbo_Wales|Evil One]], and the fake Jesus [[pwn|dies in a hail of Uzi bullets]], leading to a Jew-run world of peace and love. (Obviously a [[lulz|comedy]].)

